Problem 1

Critiquing Graphs:

This graph appeared in the January edition of the Journal of the American Statistical Association: http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/pdf/10.1080/01621459.2015.1106790

The graph shows changes in the number of statistics degrees granted annually over time. The x-axis indicates year, the y-axis indicates count, and four lines are plotted in different colors to indicate the type of degree granted.

The graphs main goal is to show theres been an increase in completion of Statistics programs, and to that end it does a decent job. There is a clear upward slope in most of the lines. Unfortunately, the graph has many serious problems. Probably the worst aspect of the graph is that the x-axis is not evenly spaced in time. This means that the slopes distort the actual rate of change and its unclear when data was actually collected. It would probably be clearer to use a faceted scatterplot. This would preserve time increments, make it clear when data was collected, and visually separate the four categories.

The graph also uses many unnecessary visual effects. Using a color gradient for the background is distracting and serves no purpose. The lines in the chart also have a gradient for no discernable reason. The axes use a gradient too. All of these gradients should be removed.

The graphics text only adds to the confusion. Neither of the axes are labeled. The title does not help indicate the purpose of the plot. Two of the categories are given the same name, and the differences are clarified in small print elsewhere on the graph. This problem comes from the fact that one of the categories is actually a subset of the other. It could be clarified by splitting them into two distinct sets.

2-D Bar Charts and (Empirical) Conditional Distributions

Do Problem 5 of Lab 03. The text from that problem is copied here:

  1. Recreate the graph from problem 1 (of Lab 03), but color each bar by the airline_sentiment variable. As always, make sure your graph is properly labeled/titled/colored and has a legend.
# Load in the airline data
library(ggplot2)
airline_tweets <- read.csv("https://dl.dropboxusercontent.com/u/18473260/Tweets.csv")
# Create a bar chart of the airline variable colored by airline sentiment
ggplot(data = airline_tweets, aes(x = airline)) +
  geom_bar() +
  aes(fill = airline_sentiment) +
  ggtitle("Bar Chart of Tweets about Airlines Colored by Sentiment") +
  labs(x = "Airline", y = "Count") +
  scale_fill_discrete(guide = guide_legend(title = "Airline Sentiment"))

  1. Where on the graph would we find the (empirical) conditional distribution of airline_sentiment given that our airline is US Airways?

The conditional distribution of airline sentiment is in each stacked bar. Given US Airways, the distributions of each sentiment are colored on the US Airways bar and we can compare the heights of each.

  1. Create a new graph that shows the conditional distribution of airline given airline_sentiment. That is, you should now have three vertical bars, each of which is colored by the airline variable.
# Create graph to show conditional distribution of airline given airline sentiment
ggplot(data = airline_tweets, aes(x = airline_sentiment)) +
  geom_bar() +
  aes(fill = airline) +
  ggtitle("Bar Chart of Airline Sentiments Colored by Airline") +
  labs(x = "Airline Sentiment", y = "Count") +
  scale_fill_discrete(guide = guide_legend(title = "Airline"))

  1. Create a side-by-side version of the chart in (c). To do this, specify position = position_dodge() in your call to geom_bar(). This tells ggplot to reposition the bars to be side-by-side.
# Create side by side bar charts
ggplot(data = airline_tweets, aes(x = airline_sentiment)) +
  geom_bar(position = position_dodge()) +
  aes(fill = airline) +
  ggtitle("Bar Chart of Airline Sentiments Colored by Airline") +
  labs(x = "Airline Sentiment", y = "Count") +
  scale_fill_discrete(guide = guide_legend(title = "Airline"))

  1. Which graph to you prefer the graph in (c), or the graph in (d)? Why? Discuss the advantages and disadvantages of both.

The advantages of stacked bar charts are the you can see the proportion of all positive tweets comprised by each airline compared to the others. You can also easily compare total quantities of tweets for each sentiment (i.e.the marginal distribution of airline_sentiment). The disadvantages are that it is hard to compare two different sentiment amounts for the same airline (i.e.comparing across conditional distributions). Its also difficult to compare the heights of each stacked bar within each conditional distribution (e.g.the relative proportions of US Airways and United in one of the sentiments).

The advantages of the side-by-side bar charts are that you can see the individual counts for each sentiment by airline (the conditional distributions of airline given each airline_sentiment cateogry), and it is easy to compare actual counts both within and across these conditional distributions. The biggest disadvantage is that its difficult to determine the marginal distribution of the first variable (airline_sentiment in this case).

Statistical Information in Bar Charts

Lets explore the birth.year variable. First, we want to remove any NAs from our birthyear data.

  1. Use the na.omit() function to remove any row that has an NA in any column. Store the subset of data with no NAs in a new object called bike_data_no_NA. How many rows does the dataset have now?
bike_data_no_NA <- na.omit(bike_data)
nrow(bike_data_no_NA)
## [1] 717

There are 717 rows.

  1. Create a new variable called birth_decade that specifies the riders decade of birth. There are several ways to do this, but for now, take the substring of the first three characters of birth-year, e.g.: bike_data_no_NA$birth_decade <- substr(bike_data_no_NA$birth.year, 1, 3). This will add a column to your data.frame called birth_decade, where, e.g., 196 represents 1960s.
bike_data_no_NA$birth_decade <- substr(bike_data_no_NA$birth.year, 1, 3)
  1. Look up the help documentation for the paste() function. How can you use the paste() function to add the string 0s to the end of your decade variable so the decades are properly formatted? Do this.
bike_data_no_NA$birth_decade <- paste(bike_data_no_NA$birth_decade, "0s",
                                      sep="")

The paste function takes a vector and pastes the string in the second argument to the end of each element of the vector, separated by the given argument sep.

  1. Make a bar chart of the decade variable. Make sure that the decades are displayed in a logical order. Make sure you use a proper title and axis labels.
base_plot <- ggplot(bike_data_no_NA, aes(x=birth_decade))
base_plot + geom_bar() + ggtitle("Counts of Bikers From Each Decade") + 
  labs(x="Decade", y="Count")

  1. Describe the distribution of birth_decade in your bar chart. Which decades are most common? Which are least common? Are there any chronological trends (linear or otherwise)?

The most common decade is the 1980s. The least common is the 1930s. The number of bikers generally increases for younger age groups until a steep drop off in the 1990s. Theres also an apparent dip in the 1970s, which suggests the age distribution may be bimodal.

  1. Recreate the same graph, but use proportions instead of counts/frequencies on the y-axis. Add error bars corresponding to an approximate 95% confidence interval around the proportion of observations in each category. Describe any relationships you see.
counts <- table(bike_data_no_NA$birth_decade)
decades <- names(counts)
proportions <- as.numeric(counts/sum(counts))
error_widths <- sqrt(proportions*(1-proportions)/sum(counts))
lower <- proportions - 1.96 * error_widths
upper <- proportions + 1.96 * error_widths
prop_data <- data.frame(decades, proportions, lower, upper)
ggplot(prop_data, aes(x=decades, y=proportions)) + geom_bar(stat="identity") +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=lower, ymax=upper)) + 
  ggtitle("Proportions of Riders by Decade") + labs(x="Decade", y="Proportion")

The error bars suggest that many of the proportions by decade are significantly different from each other. For example, the dip in the 1970s appears to be significant since its error bar does not overlap with those of the 1960s and 1980s. We could use a chi-square test to control for making many implicit comparisons. We also dont seem to have evidence of a difference in proportion between the 1960s and 1980s.

  1. Run a chi-square test where the null hypothesis is that all decades in your data have an equal proportion of observations. What is the resulting p-value? What do you conclude regarding the null hypothesis?
chisq.test(counts)
## 
##  Chi-squared test for given probabilities
## 
## data:  counts
## X-squared = 395.43, df = 6, p-value < 2.2e-16

The p-value is very 0 close to zero, indicating that there is evidence to reject the null hypothesis at any reasonable level of statistical significance (e.g.alpha = 0.001). We can conclude that the distribution of biker counts by birth decade is not uniform.

  1. Repeat parts (f) and (g), but using a subset of riders born in the 1960s, 1970s, and 1980s. To do this, you can use the following code to get the correct subset of data: bike_data_60s_70s_80s <- subset(bike_data_no_NA, birth_decade %in% c("1960s", "1970s", "1980s")). Do any of your conclusions change?
bike_data_60s_70s_80s <- subset(bike_data_no_NA, 
                                birth_decade %in% c("1960s", "1970s", "1980s"))
counts <- table(bike_data_60s_70s_80s$birth_decade)
decades <- names(counts)
proportions <- as.numeric(counts/sum(counts))
error_widths <- sqrt(proportions*(1-proportions)/sum(counts))
lower <- proportions - 1.96 * error_widths
upper <- proportions + 1.96 * error_widths
prop_data <- data.frame(decades, proportions, lower, upper)
ggplot(prop_data, aes(x=decades, y=proportions)) + geom_bar(stat="identity") +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=lower, ymax=upper)) + 
  ggtitle("Proportions of Riders by Decade") + labs(x="Decade", y="Proportion")

chisq.test(counts)
## 
##  Chi-squared test for given probabilities
## 
## data:  counts
## X-squared = 14.386, df = 2, p-value = 0.0007518

The p-value is now 0.0007518. This is still small enough to reject the null hypothesis at almost any common significance level. Therefore we can conclude that the distribution is not uniform even among this subset of decades. The error bars still indicate that a significantly smaller proportion of riders were born in the 1970s.

Problem 5

(5 points each)

2-D Bar Charts

For parts (a) and (b), use the grid.arrange function to arrange your graphs into a 1x2 grid. For all parts, be sure to use the bike_data_no_NA version of our dataset NOT the subset from the 1960s, 70s, and 80s.

  1. Create a stacked bar chart that shows the (empirical) conditional distributions of gender given each birth_decade. Be sure to use a proper title, proper labels, and easily understandable and labeled colors. Describe your graph. Which gender is more common? Does this change depending on the decade? Feel free to reference the online Citi Bike documentation to help you decode the genders.

(See graph below.) With this graph, we can examine both the marginal distribution of birth decade, and the conditional distribution of gender by birth decade. Most riders were born in the 1960s, 70s, and 80s. Generally, as we get into later decades (younger riders), the number of riders increases. This continues until the 1990s, when there is a steep drop-off (likely due to an age requirement for riders).

Male riders are more common than female riders. There are more men (gender = 1) for each birth decade except for the 1940s where there are more women (gender = 2). We notice that gender is split into three categories and that there is an unknown gender observation coded as a 0 from the 1950s decade. If this were a real report, we may consider this observation as erroneously recorded and exclude it from final analyses or graphs. That said, the observation may be informative. In cases such as these, we should be careful before removing the observation from the graphic until we have researched the issue in more detail.

  1. Create a side-by-side bar chart that shows the (empirical) conditional distributions of gender given each birth_decade. Be sure to use a proper title, proper labels, and easily understandable and labeled colors. Describe your graph.

We gain similar insight from this plot. We see that there are more women from the 1940s than men, but more men in every other decade. Overall the patterns are similar. We still a slightly normal distribution of birth decade, but it is harder to see.

library(gridExtra)

bike_data_no_NA$gender <- factor(bike_data_no_NA$gender, labels=c("Unknown", "Male", "Female")) # make sure gender is a factor and change the categores from 0, 1, 2, to the more meaningful unknown, men, women

plot1 <- ggplot(bike_data_no_NA, aes(birth_decade, fill=gender)) + geom_bar() + xlab("Birth Decade") + ylab("Count") + ggtitle("Distribution of Birth Decade by Gender")

plot2 <- ggplot(bike_data_no_NA, aes(birth_decade, fill=gender)) + geom_bar(position = "dodge") + xlab("Birth Decade") + ylab("Count") + ggtitle("Comparison of Birth Decade Distribution by Gender")

grid.arrange(plot1, plot2, ncol=2)

  1. Which graph do you prefer? Why? Justify your choice.

No right answer, as long as it is justified properly. It depends what you are looking for. If you are interested in the marginal distribution of birth decade, the first graph is a little better, since this information can be easily obtained by comparing the heights of the bars to the y-axis. If you are interested in the differences between gender for each birth decade (i.e.the conditional distributions of gender given birth_decade), the second graph is better. In general, with a stacked bar chart, its easier to see the marginal distribution of the first variable although its hard to compare the sizes of the stacked bars. With the side-by-side bar chart, its easier to compare the heights of the bars in the conditional distribution of variable 2 given variable 1.

One additional disadvantage of the side-by-side bar chart, in this case, is in the handling of the unknown gender (gender == 0). Since the unknown gender only appears in the 1950s portion of the graph, the vertical bars in this portion are squeezed into the same horizontal space. This distorts the perceived conditional distributions when comparing to other decades, since the areas are smaller. The stacked bar chart does a much better job of handling this.

(Note: There are ways to avoid this issue, which we may get to later in the semester.)

plot.b <- ggplot(bike_data_no_NA, aes(gender, fill=birth_decade)) + geom_bar(position = "dodge") + xlab("Gender") + ylab("Count") + ggtitle("Comparison of birth decade distribution for each gender")

  1. above

  2. above

  3. There are more males than females by over 300 people, or nearly three times as many. Gender is often coded as a binary variable (male/female), but in this case it is categorical (with 3 levels) because of the rider in the unknown category. It is easier to see this in graph (a) because the bars are stacked.

  4. There is a roughly equal number of female riders born in the 1940s as there are in the 50s and 60s. The 1980s was the decade with the most female riders, while the 1950s and 1990s had the fewest riders. It is much easier to gather this information visually in graph (b).

  5. The 1960s and 1980s were the two most common decades for male riders, followed by the 1970s and the 1950s. The 1930s, 1940s, and 1990s were substantially less common birth decades than these other decades, which makes sense given the ages of potential riders born in these decades.

  6. The most obvious similarities are that the 1960s, 70s, and 80s were the most common birth decades for both genders, while the 1930s and 1990s were among the least common for both. One interesting difference in these two conditional distributions is that the relative proportion of riders born in the 1940s is substantially larger for women than for men. Note that when comparing these conditional distributions, we should not comment on or compare the magnitudes of each category across these conditional distributions. This is because these magnitudes depend in large part on the marginal distribution of gender. Instead, we should only compare the relative proportions of each birth_decade across the genders. Later in the semester, well learn how to scale the y-axis by proportion instead of count, which would make these conditional distributions more easily comparable.

  7. No right answer, but I personally prefer vertical bar charts (a, b). As far as deciding between a stacked vs.a side-by-side bar chart, this depends on the purpose of the graph. Please refer to the discussion in Problem 5 part (c) for more information.
